00:30:53,811 --> 00:30:55,688
All right, stay close.

299
00:31:12,371 --> 00:31:14,123
Let's finish this.

300
00:31:19,420 --> 00:31:20,880
Put the gun down.

301
00:31:23,591 --> 00:31:25,426
I don't want to kill you.

302
00:31:28,762 --> 00:31:30,764
We both know that's a lie.

303
00:31:35,895 --> 00:31:39,106
Get down! Get behind the car!
Over there!

304
00:31:51,911 --> 00:31:54,163
What the fuck happened?

305
00:31:55,205 --> 00:31:57,374
He has the keys.

306
00:31:57,499 --> 00:31:59,835
- Let's move!
- Come on, get in the car!

307
00:31:59,960 --> 00:32:01,629
Let's go!

308
00:32:01,754 --> 00:32:02,922
- You drive.
- Patricia!

309
00:32:03,047 --> 00:32:06,967
Don't look!
Don't look! Don't look! Don't look!

310
00:32:09,136 --> 00:32:12,765
- Don't look at that!
- What the fuck is he doing here?

311
00:32:12,890 --> 00:32:15,643
He saved your life!
Get in the fucking car!

312
00:32:15,768 --> 00:32:17,436
Open! Open!

313
00:32:18,270 --> 00:32:21,649
Be careful, be careful. Okay.

314
00:32:21,774 --> 00:32:23,233
Move, move, move, move!

315
00:32:36,538 --> 00:32:38,707
What happened? Huh?

316
00:32:39,792 --> 00:32:41,335
They killed Navegante.

317
00:32:43,629 --> 00:32:46,966
- And Pallomari?
- The motherfucker's gone.

318
00:32:48,050 --> 00:32:49,468
You sure?

319
00:32:53,931 --> 00:32:56,600
We're going to the airport.
We're going to catch those...

320
00:32:56,725 --> 00:32:59,812
We're leaving, now!
Motherfuckers!

321
00:33:04,566 --> 00:33:06,402
You, come with me.

322
00:33:08,112 --> 00:33:11,865
We're going to the airport.
Take the guys. Now, now, now!

323
00:33:19,790 --> 00:33:24,461
That's the North Valley, you fuckers.
Who do they think they're messing with?

324
00:33:24,586 --> 00:33:26,714
You just got smoked, bitches.

325
00:33:34,596 --> 00:33:35,806
Boss!

326
00:33:37,307 --> 00:33:38,517
Boss!

327
00:33:52,865 --> 00:33:54,867
Let's go. Out.

328
00:33:55,701 --> 00:33:58,078
- Could you open, please?
- Yes. There you go.

329
00:33:58,203 --> 00:33:59,455
Thank you.

330
00:33:59,580 --> 00:34:03,208
Patricia, get out this way.
Careful, my love.

331
00:34:03,333 --> 00:34:04,626
Okay.

332
00:34:05,711 --> 00:34:09,131
- What's this?
- You're wanted by the CNP.

333
00:34:09,256 --> 00:34:12,843
We can't aid the escape of a fugitive,
so you've gotta fly yourself out.

334
00:34:13,761 --> 00:34:16,055
Do you see that?
We have a private plane.

335
00:34:16,180 --> 00:34:18,390
We have a plane just for us.

336
00:34:18,515 --> 00:34:22,770
- If you could sign here, sir?
- Me? Okay. Yeah.

337
00:34:23,479 --> 00:34:26,607
You have to pay for the plane.
Whatever you have on you.

338
00:34:27,775 --> 00:34:29,860
I don't carry that kind of cash...

339
00:34:29,985 --> 00:34:33,822
It's just a technicality.
So that it's not kidnapping.

340
00:34:33,947 --> 00:34:36,784
Just a moment.
If it's just a technicality...

341
00:34:38,702 --> 00:34:41,997
- Thanks. Okay.
- Okay.

342
00:34:42,122 --> 00:34:44,917
Get on the plane. Go.
Everything's going to be fine.

343
00:34:45,042 --> 00:34:47,377
Come on. Let's go.

344
00:34:52,382 --> 00:34:53,842
Goodbye, Salcedo.

345
00:35:24,039 --> 00:35:28,168
Ladies and gentlemen, my next witness
has direct, first-hand knowledge

346
00:35:28,293 --> 00:35:32,798
of the criminal activities uncovered
by Operation Cornerstone.

347
00:35:32,923 --> 00:35:34,675
Please state your name, sir.

348
00:35:35,717 --> 00:35:37,302
Guillermo Pallomari.

349
00:35:37,427 --> 00:35:39,638
And you were an accountant
for the Cali cartel?

350
00:35:39,763 --> 00:35:43,142
No, I was the chief accountant.
The chief<i>. El jefe.</i>

351
00:35:43,267 --> 00:35:45,811
'Guillermo Pallomari
had a lot to say.

352
00:35:45,936 --> 00:35:48,897
'And he said it in federal courtrooms
from Miami to New York City.'

353
00:35:49,022 --> 00:35:52,359
This is the ledger of Mr. Pallomaro
that only he himself can interpret.

354
00:35:52,484 --> 00:35:56,655
I'm sorry, your Honour, my English is not
quite good, but his Spanish is awful.

355
00:35:56,780 --> 00:35:59,199
Can you repeat my name?
"Pallomari." It's so simple.

356
00:35:59,324 --> 00:36:01,869
'And people were interested
in what he had to say,

357
00:36:01,994 --> 00:36:05,205
'especially about the cartel's influence
with the Colombian government.

358
00:36:05,330 --> 00:36:07,332
'So that government
went on the defensive.'

359
00:36:07,457 --> 00:36:10,711
'And we have total
agreement in that these testimonies

360
00:36:10,836 --> 00:36:16,175
'that we have heard from Mr. Pallomari
are ridiculous and grotesquely false.

361
00:36:16,300 --> 00:36:17,551
'Thank you very much.'

362
00:36:17,676 --> 00:36:19,469
'But the damage was done.

363
00:36:19,595 --> 00:36:22,973
'It would be most helpful if the Colombian
president, who's head of the government,

364
00:36:23,098 --> 00:36:25,225
'was as dedicated
to fighting narcotics trafficking

365
00:36:25,350 --> 00:36:27,269
'as many of the people
in his own government.'

366
00:36:27,394 --> 00:36:30,731
'The U.S. House and Senate
began making noise about decertification,

367
00:36:30,856 --> 00:36:35,068
'turning Colombia from an ally
in The War on Drugs into an enemy,

368
00:36:35,194 --> 00:36:37,112
'threatening to choke off
the vital foreign aid

369
00:36:37,237 --> 00:36:40,532
'that served the shadowy interests
of both nations.

370
00:36:40,657 --> 00:36:42,326
'And that scared people.

371
00:36:42,451 --> 00:36:47,456
'Enough to see justice finally done?
Well, governments don't work that way.'

372
00:36:47,581 --> 00:36:49,374
You know how many times
I've gotten a call

373
00:36:49,499 --> 00:36:52,085
from the Department of Justice and State
the same morning?

374
00:36:53,921 --> 00:36:58,300
Count 'em on one finger.
Guess we have you to thank for that.

375
00:36:59,134 --> 00:37:01,345
I'm headed over
to the National Palace right now,

376
00:37:01,470 --> 00:37:07,142
to make clear to President Samper himself
that the godfathers stay in jail.

377
00:37:07,267 --> 00:37:11,271
- At least for the foreseeable future.
- But that's as far as it goes?

378
00:37:15,150 --> 00:37:18,862
We drew up a draft indictment outlining
President Samper's ties to the Cali cartel.

379
00:37:18,987 --> 00:37:20,656
Alleged ties.

380
00:37:21,865 --> 00:37:24,743
And I suggest you keep that draft
to yourself.

381
00:37:24,868 --> 00:37:28,455
The DOJ's not going to topple
a government, Agent Peña.

382
00:37:31,500 --> 00:37:34,336
You can't tell me
you're surprised by that.

383
00:37:35,671 --> 00:37:39,383
Some part of me
was holding out hope, I guess.

384
00:37:41,093 --> 00:37:44,304
Well, you should tell that part
to grow the fuck up.

385
00:37:44,429 --> 00:37:47,766
No, I mean it, Agent Peña.
You should be happy.

386
00:37:47,891 --> 00:37:49,977
You played the system
like a goddamn fiddle.

387
00:37:53,105 --> 00:37:55,816
You won.

388
00:38:03,824 --> 00:38:05,450
Yes, sir.

389
00:38:16,169 --> 00:38:18,171
'Another deal.

390
00:38:19,673 --> 00:38:21,675
'A compromise.

391
00:38:23,427 --> 00:38:25,429
'A charade.

392
00:38:27,347 --> 00:38:29,141
'A way for governments
who don't give a shit

393
00:38:29,266 --> 00:38:31,560
'about the war
they're supposed to be fighting...

394
00:38:33,145 --> 00:38:35,689
'to go on pretending they're winning it.

395
00:38:36,732 --> 00:38:38,734
'But it can't be won.

396
00:38:40,360 --> 00:38:42,362
'It'll never be won.

397
00:38:44,072 --> 00:38:46,992
'At least not until people see it
for what it is.

398
00:38:50,037 --> 00:38:52,164
'Not until they know the truth.'

399
00:39:19,816 --> 00:39:23,653
You know what it means
if you go on the record, right?

400
00:39:24,571 --> 00:39:26,865
There'll be a price to pay.

401
00:39:28,658 --> 00:39:30,494
Press the button.

402
00:39:34,706 --> 00:39:37,542
Let's start with your name
and occupation.

403
00:39:42,172 --> 00:39:46,843
Javier Peña,
DEA attaché in Colombia.

404
00:39:50,430 --> 00:39:52,516
'And so the truth got out.

405
00:39:52,641 --> 00:39:57,145
'The news that the Cali cartel had
donated to the president's campaign

406
00:39:57,270 --> 00:40:00,524
'in exchange for virtual immunity

407
00:40:00,649 --> 00:40:03,360
'turned Colombia upside down.

408
00:40:03,485 --> 00:40:08,490
'And when the highest-ranking DEA agent
in the country went on the record

409
00:40:08,615 --> 00:40:11,618
'and said not only did
the United States know about it,

410
00:40:11,743 --> 00:40:14,621
'but we allowed it to happen,

411
00:40:14,746 --> 00:40:16,665
'they couldn't hide from it anymore.'

412
00:40:16,790 --> 00:40:18,625
'In an exclusive interview,

413
00:40:18,750 --> 00:40:21,878
'he accuses the country
of being a Narco-Democracy.

414
00:40:22,003 --> 00:40:24,339
'He said the country
has fallen into the abyss.

415
00:40:24,464 --> 00:40:28,051
'His words have not been well received
by the Colombian people.

416
00:40:28,176 --> 00:40:31,680
'The public is demanding
an official response...'

417
00:40:42,190 --> 00:40:46,445
You didn't really call the country that
we're guests in a "Narco-Democracy"?

418
00:40:46,570 --> 00:40:48,780
- Are you saying it isn't?
- The State Department's livid.

419
00:40:48,905 --> 00:40:52,451
Good.
